    <stitle>MOR/RYDE RUBBER SPRING SUSPENSION - REPLACEMENT - CROSSMEMBER STRAPS</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc id="hl0300906" svcproctype="replace" graphiccount="1">
        <title>CROSSMEMBER STRAPS</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <para>The crossmember straps (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0300905">Figure 5</hotlnk>) are very critical parts in assuring the integrity of the
                suspension system. The purpose of these crossmember straps is to keep the bottoms of the hangers from
                spreading apart. Failure to repair broken or loose crossmember straps will always result in the fracture
                of the hanger assembly and/or the chassis side-members. Most crossmember strap failures are due to the
                1/2" attaching bolts not being properly tightened.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0300905" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0300905" filename="../figg03/G0300905.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 5. CROSSMEMBER STRAPS</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Remove</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Make sure vehicle is elevated, chassis is supported with safety stands, the front wheels
                    blocked and the suspension hanging unsupported.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove bolts/nuts securing crossmember strap. Remove crossmember strap.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Install</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new crossmember strap.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install all bolts/nuts securing crossmember finger tight.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tighten nuts to 69 ft-lbs. (94 N&#8226;m).</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
